{"title_page": "1953 in animation", "text_new": "{{Year box}}\nEvents in '''1953 in animation'''.\n\n==Events==\n\n===January===\n* '''January 3''': [[Chuck Jones]]'s ''[[Don't Give Up the Sheep]]'' premiers, which marks the debut of [[Ralph Wolf and Sam Sheepdog]]. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045697/</ref>\n\n===February===\n* '''February 5''': [[Clyde Geronimi]], [[Wilfred Jackson]] and [[Hamilton Luske]]'s ''[[Peter Pan (1953 film)|Peter Pan]]'', produced by the [[Walt Disney Company]], is first released. The film marks the debut of [[Tinkerbell]] within the Disney franchise, who will later become one of their mascots. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0046183/</ref>\n* '''February 28''': [[Chuck Jones]]' ''[[Daffy Duck]]'' cartoon ''[[Duck Amuck]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045708/</ref>\n\n===March===\n* '''March 19''': [[25th Academy Awards]]: [[Hanna-Barbera]]'s ''[[Tom & Jerry]]'' short ''[[Johann Mouse]]'' wins the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short]].<ref name=\"Oscars1953\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1953 |title=The 25th Academy Awards (1953) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=2011-08-20 |publisher=Oscars.org ([[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706093830/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/25th-winners.html |archivedate=6 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is the seventh and final ''[[Tom & Jerry]]'' cartoon to win an Oscar. <ref>https://www.lambiek.net/artists/b/barbera_joseph.htm</ref> The animated short receives it's official public premier on 21 March. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045937/</ref>\n* '''March 27''': [[Karel Zeman]]'s first animated feature ''[[The Treasure of Bird Island]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045040/</ref>\n\n===April===\n* '''April 8''': [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Trnka]]'s ''[[Old Czech Legends]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0240034/</ref>\n* '''April 15-29''': [[1953 Cannes Film Festival]]: \n** [[Walt Disney]] receives a \"Legion of Honour\" during the opening ceremony. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://fresques.ina.fr/festival-de-cannes-en/fiche-media/Cannes00014/opening-of-the-1953-festival.html |title=Opening of the 1953 festival |work=fresques.ina.fr |accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VMLLTapCpEUC&pg=PA133&lpg=PA133&dq=walt+disney+honoured+at+1953+cannes+film+festival&source=bl&ots=OGrrZ7JyEx&sig=AYHt9BnifWuoE_VIa7fa1gnhsxw&hl=en&sa=X&ei=chi7UqnDDsfH0QXtnYDwDQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=walt%20disney%20honoured%20at%201953%20cannes%20film%20festival&f=false |work=books.google.com |title=Walt Disney honoured at 1953 cannes film festival |accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n** ''[[The Romance of Transportation in Canada]]'' by [[Colin Low (filmmaker)|Colin Low]] wins the [[Short Film Palme d'Or]]. <ref>http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/films/the-romance-of-transportation-in-canada</ref>\n* '''April 25''': [[Hanna-Barbera]]'s ''[[Tom & Jerry]]'' short ''[[That's My Pup!]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0046417/</ref>\n\n===May===\n* '''May 2''': [[Friz Freleng]]'s ''[[Bugs Bunny]]'' and ''[[Yosemite Sam]]'' short ''[[Southern Fried Rabbit]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0046350/</ref> \n\n===June===\n* '''June 19''': The animated advertisement ''[[Let's All Go to the Lobby]]'' by [[Dave Fleischer]] premiers, intended to invite moviegoers to get themselves something to eat and drink during intermissions. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0272170/</ref>\n\n===July===\n* '''July 25''': [[Chuck Jones]]' ''[[Duck Dodgers in the 24\u00bdth Century]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045709/</ref>\n\n===August===\n* '''August 8''': [[Chuck Jones]]' ''[[Bully for Bugs]]'' premiers, in which [[Bugs Bunny]] becomes a bull-fighter. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045585/</ref>\n* '''August 29''': [[Bob McKimson]]'s ''[[Cat-Tails For Two]]'' is first released, which marks the debut of [[Speedy Gonzales]]. <ref>https://www.bcdb.com/cartoon/3743-Cat-Tails-For-Two</ref><ref>https://www.lambiek.net/artists/m/mckimson_bob.htm</ref>\n\n===September===\n* '''September 5''': [[Hanna-Barbera]]'s ''[[Tom & Jerry]]'' short  ''[[Just Ducky]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045946/</ref>\n* '''September 11''': [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Trnka]]'s ''[[Old Czech Legends]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0240034/</ref>\n* '''September 26''': [[Chuck Jones]]' ''[[Bugs Bunny]]'' short ''[[Lumber Jack-Rabbit]]'' premiers, a cartoon made in [[3-D film|3-D]]. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0047196/</ref>\n\n===October===\n* '''October 3''': [[Chuck Jones]]' ''[[Duck! Rabbit, Duck!]]'' premiers, the third film in the \"hunting season\" trilogy starring [[Bugs Bunny]],  [[Daffy Duck]] and [[Elmer Fudd]].<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045710/</ref>\n* '''October 10''': ''[[Winky Dink and You]]'', the first interactive TV series, which invites viewers to use a special crayon to draw on the screen, is first broadcast. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045456/releaseinfo?ref_=tt_dt_dt</ref>\n* '''October 30''': [[Jean Image]]'s ''[[Bonjour Paris]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.unifrance.org/film/4787/bonjour-paris</ref>\n\n===November===\n* '''November 10''': \n** [[Hamilton Luske]]'s ''[[Ben and Me]]'', produced by the [[Walt Disney Company]], is released, a cartoon about [[Benjamin Franklin]]. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045550/</ref>\n** [[Ward Kimball]] and [[Charles August Nichols|Charles A. Nichols]]' ''[[Toot, Whistle, Plunk and Boom]]'', produced by the [[Walt Disney Company]], premiers. It is the first Disney cartoon to be filmed and released in widescreen [[Cinemascope]]. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0046442/</ref>\n\n===December===\n* '''December 17''': Ted Parmelee's ''[[The Tell-Tale Heart (1953 American film)|The Tell-Tale Heart]]'', produced by [[UPA (animation studio)|UPA]], premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0046408/</ref>\n* '''December 21''': [[Walter Lantz]] productions releases ''[[Chilly Willy (film)|Chilly Willy]]'', directed by [[Paul Smith (animator)|Paul J. Smith]], which marks the debut of [[Chilly Willy]] the penguin. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0487237/</ref>\n\n===Specific date unknown===\n* [[Carl Urbano]]'s promotional cartoon ''[[A Is for Atom]]'' is released, which explains how [[atomic energy]] works. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0401091/releaseinfo?ref_=tt_dt_dt</ref>\n\n==Films released==\n{{Main|List of animated feature films of the 1950s}}\n\n== Television series ==\n{{Main|List of animated television series of the 1940s and 1950s}}\n\n==Deaths==\n\n===August===\n* '''August 3''': [[Harry E. Lang]], American voice actor (voice of [[Tom Cat|Tom]] in a few ''[[Tom & Jerry]]'' cartoons), dies at age 58 from a heart attack. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0485764/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of anime by release date (1946\u20131959)]]\n\n{{Years of animation}}\n\n[[Category:1953 in animation| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Year box}}\nEvents in '''1953 in animation'''.\n\n==Events==\n\n===January===\n* '''January 3''': [[Chuck Jones]]'s ''[[Don't Give Up the Sheep]]'' premiers, which marks the debut of [[Ralph Wolf and Sam Sheepdog]]. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045697/</ref>\n\n===February===\n* '''February 5''': [[Clyde Geronimi]], [[Wilfred Jackson]] and [[Hamilton Luske]]'s ''[[Peter Pan (1953 film)|Peter Pan]]'', produced by the [[Walt Disney Company]], is first released. The film marks the debut of [[Tinkerbell]] within the Disney franchise, who will later become one of their mascots. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0046183/</ref>\n* '''February 28''': [[Chuck Jones]]' ''[[Daffy Duck]]'' cartoon ''[[Duck Amuck]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045708/</ref>\n\n===March===\n* '''March 19''': [[25th Academy Awards]]: [[Hanna-Barbera]]'s ''[[Tom & Jerry]]'' short ''[[Johann Mouse]]'' wins the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short]].<ref name=\"Oscars1953\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1953 |title=The 25th Academy Awards (1953) Nominees and Winners |accessdate=2011-08-20 |publisher=Oscars.org ([[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]) |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706093830/http://www.oscars.org/awards/academyawards/legacy/ceremony/25th-winners.html |archivedate=6 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> It is the seventh and final ''[[Tom & Jerry]]'' cartoon to win an Oscar. <ref>https://www.lambiek.net/artists/b/barbera_joseph.htm</ref> The animated short receives it's official public premier on 21 March. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045937/</ref>\n* '''March 27''': [[Karel Zeman]]'s first animated feature ''[[The Treasure of Bird Island]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045040/</ref>\n\n===April===\n* '''April 8''': [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Trnka]]'s ''[[Old Czech Legends]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0240034/</ref>\n* '''April 15-29''': [[1953 Cannes Film Festival]]: \n** [[Walt Disney]] receives a \"Legion of Honour\" during the opening ceremony. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://fresques.ina.fr/festival-de-cannes-en/fiche-media/Cannes00014/opening-of-the-1953-festival.html |title=Opening of the 1953 festival |work=fresques.ina.fr |accessdate=8 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VMLLTapCpEUC&pg=PA133&lpg=PA133&dq=walt+disney+honoured+at+1953+cannes+film+festival&source=bl&ots=OGrrZ7JyEx&sig=AYHt9BnifWuoE_VIa7fa1gnhsxw&hl=en&sa=X&ei=chi7UqnDDsfH0QXtnYDwDQ&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=walt%20disney%20honoured%20at%201953%20cannes%20film%20festival&f=false |work=books.google.com |title=Walt Disney honoured at 1953 cannes film festival |accessdate=25 May 2017}}</ref>\n** ''[[The Romance of Transportation in Canada]]'' by [[Colin Low (filmmaker)|Colin Low]] wins the [[Short Film Palme d'Or]]. <ref>http://www.festival-cannes.com/en/films/the-romance-of-transportation-in-canada</ref>\n* '''April 25''': [[Hanna-Barbera]]'s ''[[Tom & Jerry]]'' short ''[[That's My Pup!]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0046417/</ref>\n\n===May===\n* '''May 2''': [[Friz Freleng]]'s ''[[Bugs Bunny]]'' and ''[[Yosemite Sam]]'' short ''[[Southern Fried Rabbit]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0046350/</ref> \n\n===June===\n* '''June 19''': The animated advertisement ''[[Let's All Go to the Lobby]]'' by [[Dave Fleischer]] premiers, intended to invite moviegoers to get themselves something to eat and drink during intermissions. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0272170/</ref>\n\n===July===\n* '''July 25''': [[Chuck Jones]]' ''[[Duck Dodgers in the 24\u00bdth Century]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045709/</ref>\n\n===August===\n* '''August 8''': [[Chuck Jones]]' ''[[Bully for Bugs]]'' premiers, in which [[Bugs Bunny]] becomes a bull-fighter. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045585/</ref>\n* '''August 29''': [[Bob McKimson]]'s ''[[Cat-Tails For Two]]'' is first released, which marks the debut of [[Speedy Gonzales]]. <ref>https://www.bcdb.com/cartoon/3743-Cat-Tails-For-Two</ref>\n<ref>https://www.lambiek.net/artists/m/mckimson_bob.htm</ref>\n\n===September===\n* '''September 5''': [[Hanna-Barbera]]'s ''[[Tom & Jerry]]'' short  ''[[Just Ducky]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045946/</ref>\n* '''September 11''': [[Ji\u0159\u00ed Trnka]]'s ''[[Old Czech Legends]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0240034/</ref>\n* '''September 26''': [[Chuck Jones]]' ''[[Bugs Bunny]]'' short ''[[Lumber Jack-Rabbit]]'' premiers, a cartoon made in [[3-D film|3-D]]. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0047196/</ref>\n\n===October===\n* '''October 3''': [[Chuck Jones]]' ''[[Duck! Rabbit, Duck!]]'' premiers, the third film in the \"hunting season\" trilogy starring [[Bugs Bunny]],  [[Daffy Duck]] and [[Elmer Fudd]].<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045710/</ref>\n* '''October 10''': ''[[Winky Dink and You]]'', the first interactive TV series, which invites viewers to use a special crayon to draw on the screen, is first broadcast. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045456/releaseinfo?ref_=tt_dt_dt</ref>\n* '''October 30''': [[Jean Image]]'s ''[[Bonjour Paris]]'' premiers. <ref>https://www.unifrance.org/film/4787/bonjour-paris</ref>\n\n===November===\n* '''November 10''': \n** [[Hamilton Luske]]'s ''[[Ben and Me]]'', produced by the [[Walt Disney Company]], is released, a cartoon about [[Benjamin Franklin]]. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0045550/</ref>\n** [[Ward Kimball]] and [[Charles August Nichols|Charles A. Nichols]]' ''[[Toot, Whistle, Plunk and Boom]]'', produced by the [[Walt Disney Company]], premiers. It is the first Disney cartoon to be filmed and released in widescreen [[Cinemascope]]. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0046442/</ref>\n\n===December===\n* '''December 17''': Ted Parmelee's ''[[The Tell-Tale Heart (1953 American film)|The Tell-Tale Heart]]'', produced by [[UPA (animation studio)|UPA]], premiers. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0046408/</ref>\n* '''December 21''': [[Walter Lantz]] productions releases ''[[Chilly Willy (film)|Chilly Willy]]'', directed by [[Paul Smith (animator)|Paul J. Smith]], which marks the debut of [[Chilly Willy]] the penguin. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0487237/</ref>\n\n===Specific date unknown===\n* [[Carl Urbano]]'s promotional cartoon ''[[A Is for Atom]]'' is released, which explains how [[atomic energy]] works. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0401091/releaseinfo?ref_=tt_dt_dt</ref>\n\n==Films released==\n{{Main|List of animated feature films of the 1950s}}\n\n== Television series ==\n{{Main|List of animated television series of the 1940s and 1950s}}\n\n==Deaths==\n\n===August===\n* '''August 3''': [[Harry E. Lang]], American voice actor (voice of [[Tom Cat|Tom]] in a few ''[[Tom & Jerry]]'' cartoons), dies at age 58 from a heart attack. <ref>https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0485764/</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of anime by release date (1946\u20131959)]]\n\n{{Years of animation}}\n\n[[Category:1953 in animation| ]]\n", "name_user": "Dimadick", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAugust", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1953_in_animation"}
{"title_page": "Supalonely", "text_new": "{{short description|2019 single by Benee}}\n{{Infobox song\n|name=Supalonely\n|type=single\n|artist=[[Benee]] featuring [[Gus Dapperton]]\n|EP=[[Stella & Steve]]\n|released=6 December 2019\n|format={{hlist|[[Music download|Digital download]]|[[Streaming media|streaming]]}}\n|genre={{hlist|[[Disco]]<ref name=\"Idolator\" />|[[alt pop]]<ref name=\"Idolator\" />}}\n|length=3:43\n|label=[[Republic Records]]\n|writer={{hlist|[[Gus Dapperton|Brendan Patrick Rice]]|[[Jenna Andrews]]|[[Kidz in Space|Josh Fountain]]|[[Benee|Stella Rose Bennett]]}}\n|producer={{hlist|Josh Fountain|Brendan Patrick Rice}}\n|chronology=[[Benee]]\n|prev_title=[[Monsta (song)|Monsta]]\n|prev_year=2019\n|year=2019\n|misc={{external music video|type=single|{{YouTube|Rb6Scz-5YOs|Supalonely}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Supalonely'''\" is a song by New Zealand musician [[Benee]] featuring American musician [[Gus Dapperton]]. It was initially released as a song on her second extended play ''[[Stella & Steve]]'' on 15 November 2019, before becoming the EP's third and final single on 6 December 2019.<ref name=\"Bongmines\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bongminesentertainment.com/benee-supalonely-gus-dapperton/ |title=BENEE releases an upbeat alternative-pop tune, entitled, \"Supalonely\", featuring Gus Dapperton |author=Thomson, Zangba |date=3 December 2019|website=Bongmines Entertainment|accessdate= 24 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"pilerats\">{{cite web|url=http://pilerats.com/written/light-easy/must-listen-singles-benee-spacey-jane-young-franco-more/|title=This Week's Must-Listen Singles: BENEE, Spacey Jane, Young Franco + more|last=Davies|first=Hayden|date=11 December 2019|website=PILERATS|url-status=live|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref> The song gained popularity after spawning a viral dance challenge on the online video-sharing platform [[TikTok]] in March 2020.<ref name=\"Idolator\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.idolator.com/7907879/future-hit-benees-supalonely-is-absolutely-irresistible|title=Future Hit: BENEE's \"Supalonely\" Is Absolutely Irresistible|last=Wass|first=Mike|date=10 March 2020|website=[[Idolator (website)|Idolator]]|url-status=live|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.clashmusic.com/videos/benees-supalonely-is-ultra-infectious|title=BENEE's 'Supalonely' Is Ultra-Infectious|last=Murray|first=Robin|date=6 March 2020|website=[[Clash (magazine)|Clash]]|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> The song was certified Gold on its second week on the [[New Zealand Top 40]]. It peaked on the top 25 of countries such as the UK, Canada, Netherlands, Australia, Ireland, Norway, Austria, Finland and Denmark.\n\n== Critical reception ==\nOn his [[Apple Music]] show, [[Elton John]] described \"Supalonely\" as a \"smash record\", and further described Benee as \"an amazing young artist\" who \"writes really brilliantly\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Barton|first=Monika|url=https://www.newshub.co.nz/home/entertainment/2020/03/elton-john-raves-about-amazing-benee-confesses-he-s-crazy-about-six60-on-apple-music-show.html|title=Elton John raves about 'amazing' Benee, confesses he's 'crazy about' Six60 on Apple Music show|date=6 March 2020|work=Newshub|access-date=15 March 2020|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> Ariana Marsh from [[I-D|''i-D'']] wrote that the \"sunny pop\" song \"turns your typical breakup song on its head\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/jgeg8b/benee-and-gus-dapperton-turn-breakup-blues-into-sunny-pop-on-supalonely|title=BENEE and Gus Dapperton turn breakup blues into sunny pop on Supalonely|last=Marsh|first=Ariana|date=4 February 2020|website=[[i-D]]|language=en|url-status=live|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref> The song was described by Glenn Rowley of ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' as \"a quirky, knowing ode to the art of loneliness.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop/8550207/benee-supalonely-video-tour-dates|title=Benee Is 'Supalonely' in Colorful New Video, Announces North American Tour: See the Dates|last=Rowley|first=Glenn|date=5 February 2020|website=Billboard|url-status=live|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Charts ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[ARIA Charts|ARIA]])<ref name=\"ARIA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/charts/singles-chart|title=ARIA Australian Top 50 Singles|publisher=[[Australian Recording Industry Association]]|date=6 April 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 8\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|15|artist=Benee feat. Gus Dapperton|song=Supalonely|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|29|artist=Benee feat. Gus Dapperton|song=Supalonely|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia Tip|2|artist=Benee feat. Gus Dapperton|song=Supalonely|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Canada ([[Canadian Hot 100]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/search?artistname=Benee&chartcode=CAN|title=Benee, CAN|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 10\n|-\n{{single chart|Czechdigital|22|year=2020|week=14|rowheader=true|accessdate=7 April 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Denmark ([[Tracklisten]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hitlisten.nu/default.asp?w=13&y=2020&list=t40|title=Track Top-40 Uge 13, 2020|publisher=[[Hitlisten]]|accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n| 17\n|-\n{{single chart|Finland|18|artist=Benee|song=Supalonely|rowheader=true|accessdate=30 March 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|SNEP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snepmusique.com/les-tops/le-top-de-la-semaine/top-albums/?semaine=14?&annee=2020&categorie=Top%20Singles|title=Top Singles (Week 14, 2020)|publisher=[[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique]]|language=French|accessdate=7 April 2