t-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"Bongmines\"/><ref name=\"pilerats\"/>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Italy\n| 13 March 2020\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| <ref name=\"EarOne\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.earone.it/news/benee_supalonely_feat_gus_dapperton_radio_date_13_03_2020_40844412/|title=BENEE - SUPALONELY (feat. GUS DAPPERTON) (Radio Date: 13-03-2020)|website=EarOne|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| United Kingdom\n| 27 March 2020\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref name=\"BBC Radio 1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/3tqPdBWF9yMbTrfjWvfKV8t/radio-1-playlist|title=Radio 1 Playlist|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200329043719/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/3tqPdBWF9yMbTrfjWvfKV8t/radio-1-playlist|archivedate=December 6, 2019|website=[[BBC]]|access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Benee}}\n[[Category:2019 singles]]\n[[Category:TikTok songs]]\n[[Category:Republic Records singles]]\n[[Category:Benee songs]]\n[[Category:Gus Dapperton songs]]\n[[Category:2019 songs]]\n", "name_user": "Ss112", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCharts:updated", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supalonely"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea", "text_new": "{{Current disaster|event=pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in South Korea}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea\n| map1 = COVID-19 outbreak South Korea per capita cases map.svg\n| legend1 = Confirmed cases per million residents by province or city\n| map2 = Coronavirus Outbreak in South Korea over Time.gif\n| legend2 = Coronavirus pandemic in South Korea over time (since January 20, 2020).<br /><div style=\"{{linear-gradient|left|#ffffff, #ff0000}}; border:solid 1px black; width:50px; height:0.5em; float:left; position:relative; top:0.4em;\">&nbsp;</div> &nbsp; Number of cases ([[logarithmic scale|logarithmically]]){{legend|#e7e8e6|Day not included in map}}{{legend|#989896|Day included in map}}{{legend|#444443|Last day included in map}}\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| first_case = [[Incheon International Airport]]\n| location = [[South Korea]]\n| arrival_date = 20 January 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=20|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases = 6,694\n| confirmed_cases = 10,331\n| suspected_cases = 20,650\n| deaths = 192\n| total_ili =\n| website = {{URL|ncov.mohw.go.kr/en}}\n}}\nThe first confirmed case of the [[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic|pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) in [[South Korea]] was announced on 20 January 2020.<ref name=\"mk\">{{cite web |script-title=ko:\uc2e0\uc885 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4 \ud55c\uad6d\uc778 \uccab\ud658\uc790 \ud655\uc778 |url=https://www.mk.co.kr/news/society/view/2020/01/80017/ |website=MK |publisher=\uc11c\uc9c4\uc6b0 |accessdate=24 January 2020 |language=ko |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200124134926/https://www.mk.co.kr/news/society/view/2020/01/80017/ |archive-date=24 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On 19 February, the number of confirmed cases increased by 20 and on 20 February by 58<ref name=\"Getnews_58_Shincheonji\">{{cite web|url=http://m.getnews.co.kr/view.php?ud=2020022021135849202aaae0046f_16|script-title=ko:31\ubc88 \ud658\uc790 \uc5f0\uad00 \uc2e0\ucc9c\uc9c0\uad50\ud68c \ub300\ub0a8\ubcd1\uc6d0\uc11c \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 58\uba85, 1\uba85 \uc0ac\ub9dd|date=20 February 2020|title=Archived copy|access-date=21 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102733/http://m.getnews.co.kr/view.php?ud=2020022021135849202aaae0046f_16|archive-date=26 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> or 70,<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\">{{cite news | last1= Shin | first1= Hyonhee | last2= Cha | first2= Sangmi | title= 'Like a zombie apocalypse': Residents on edge as coronavirus cases surge in South Korea |trans-title = <!-- trans-title is the English translation --> | date= 20 February 2020 |agency=[[Thomson Reuters]] | url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-southkorea-cases/like-a-zombie-apocalypse-residents-on-edge-as-coronavirus-cases-surge-in-south-korea-idUSKBN20E04F |accessdate=20 February 2020 |archiveurl= https://archive.today/D1K5i |archivedate= 20 February 2020 |url-status=live <!-- live|dead|unfit|usurped --> |url-access = <!-- (subscription/registration/limited) default=free -->}}</ref> giving a total of 346 confirmed cases on 21 February 2020, according to the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention Korea]] ([[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|KCDC]]), with the sudden jump mostly attributed to \"Patient 31\" who participated in a gathering at a [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus|Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony]] church in [[Daegu]].<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: South Korea reports 161 new cases, bringing total to 763; 7th death reported |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korea-reports-161-new-cases-bringing-total-to-763 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=24 February 2020 |date=24 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224060714/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korea-reports-161-new-cases-bringing-total-to-763 |archive-date=24 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAmidst the fears of further contamination, mass gatherings in the affected cities were cancelled and a few hundred soldiers in [[Daegu]] are in isolation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Seoul city to ban rallies, Shincheonji church services to curb virus |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200221003252315 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |agency=YNA |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221112436/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200221003252315 |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Soldiers in Daegu areas banned from leaving bases, meeting visitors |url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200220003551325 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |agency=YNA |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221145843/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200220003551325 |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of 4 February 2020, in order to help prevent the spread of COVID-19, South Korea is denying entry to foreigners traveling from [[Hubei|Hubei Province]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://m.tbs.seoul.kr/efm/newsView.do?typ_800=N&idx_800=2383586&seq_800= | title=S. Korea Bars Foreigners Traveling from Hubei Province | access-date=2 March 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309151058/http://m.tbs.seoul.kr/efm/newsView.do?typ_800=N&idx_800=2383586&seq_800= | archive-date=9 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-28/as-virus-spreads-koreans-blame-refusal-to-stop-chinese-visitors |title=As Virus Spreads, Koreans Blame Refusal to Stop Chinese Visitors |publisher=Bloomberg |date=2020-02-28 |accessdate=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nAs of 24 March 2020, South Korea has about 9,037 cases and 120 deaths,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/south-korea/|title=Coronavirus South Korea|website=Worldometer|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317173023/https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/south-korea/|archive-date=17 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> with over 348,582 people having been tested, a [[case fatality rate]] of 1.33%, which is lower than the WHO's global case fatality rate of 4.34%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://coronaboard.kr/en/|title=COVID-19 Realtime Dashboard|website=COVID-19 Realtime Dashboard|access-date=24 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324053131/https://coronaboard.kr/en/|archive-date=24 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nSouth Korea introduced what was considered one of the largest and best-organised epidemic control programs in the world, along with Taiwan,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://time.com/5805629/coronavirus-taiwan/ |title=Taiwan Has Been Shut Out of Global Health Discussions |access-date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323222040/https://time.com/5805629/coronavirus-taiwan/ |archive-date=23 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Vietnam,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ft.com/content/0cc3c956-6cb2-11ea-89df-41bea055720b |title=Archived copy |access-date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324085234/https://www.ft.com/content/0cc3c956-6cb2-11ea-89df-41bea055720b |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> and Singapore.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://time.com/5802293/coronavirus-covid19-singapore-hong-kong-taiwan/ |title=Coronavirus Lessons from Singapore, Taiwan and Hong Kong |access-date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324174105/https://time.com/5802293/coronavirus-covid19-singapore-hong-kong-taiwan/ |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Different measures have been taken to screen the mass population for the virus, and isolate any infected people as well as trace and quarantine those who contacted them, without further lockdown.<ref name=science20200317 /><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-51836898 |title=Coronavirus in South Korea: How 'trace, test and treat' may be saving lives |first=Laura |last=Bicker |work=BBC |date=12 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320190601/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-51836898 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The rapid and extensive tests taken by South Korea has been judged successful in limiting the spread of the outbreak despite not using the drastic measure of quarantining entire cities.<ref name=science20200317>{{cite journal |journal=Science |url=https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-have-dropped-sharply-south-korea-whats-secret-its-success |title=Coronavirus cases have dropped sharply in South Korea. What's the secret to its success? |first=Dennis |last=Normile |date=17 March 2020 |doi=10.1126/science.abb7566 |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320205413/https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/03/coronavirus-cases-have-dropped-sharply-south-korea-whats-secret-its-success |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/south-korea-coronavirus-lessons-quick-easy-tests-monitoring-200319011438619.html |title=South Korea's coronavirus lessons: Quick, easy tests; monitoring |first=Kelly |last=Kasulis |date=19 March 2020 |work=Al Jazeera |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320144222/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/south-korea-coronavirus-lessons-quick-easy-tests-monitoring-200319011438619.html |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/20/south-korea-rapid-intrusive-measures-covid-19 |title=South Korea took rapid, intrusive measures against Covid-19 \u2013 and they worked |first1=Alexis |last1=Dudden |first2=Andrew |last2=Marks |date=20 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |access-date=20 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320143716/https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2020/mar/20/south-korea-rapid-intrusive-measures-covid-19 |archive-date=20 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn middle of March, South Korea successfully contained the Shincheonji [[Disease cluster |cluster]], however, excluding the Shincheonji cluster, the spreading trend has not diminished.<ref>{{cite web |title=\uc2e0\ucc9c\uc9c0\u00b7TK \ube7c\uba74 \ud655\uc0b0\uc138 \uaebe\uc774\uc9c0 \uc54a\uc558\ub2e4 |publisher=JoongAng Ilbo |date=23 March 2020 |url=https://news.joins.com/article/23736100 |access-date=26 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322174717/https://news.joins.com/article/23736100 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{multiple image\n | align = right\n | total_width = 200\n | direction = vertical\n\n | image1 = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in South Korea.svg\n | caption1 = Map of special cities & municipals with confirmed or suspected coronavirus cases (as of 7 April): {{legend|#c80000|Confirmed cases reported}}{{legend|#558eed|Suspected cases reported}}{{legend|#00cc00|14 days no confirmed cases}}\n\n | image2 = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in South Korea (Density).svg\n | caption2 = Map of special cities & municipals with confirmed or suspected coronavirus cases (as of 7 April): {{legend|#FCEED3|Confirmed 1\u20139}}{{legend|#F2A88D|Confirmed 10\u201399}}{{legend|#E36654|Confirmed 100\u2013499}}{{legend|#E5354B|Confirmed 500\u2013999}}{{legend|#87353F|Confirmed 1000\u20139999}}{{legend|#630606|Confirmed \u226510000}}\n\n | image3 = Confirmed Cases of Coronavirus in South Korea (English version).png\n | caption3 = Number of confirmed coronavirus cases by provinces & special cities.\n}}\n\nDuring the first four weeks, South Korea controlled the potential spread of COVID-19 by using high-tech resources like tracking the use of credit cards and checking CCTV footage of confirmed patients. However, since 18 February, the number of cases increased to more than 1,700 after discovery of the fact that patient No. 31 was a member of the [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus]]. Some media reported that was difficult for [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|KCDC]] to screen the patient because Shincheonji teaches that illness is sin. Many members were uncooperative with KCDC and could not be contacted.<ref name=fp20200227>{{cite web | url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/02/27/coronavirus-south-korea-cults-conservatives-china/ | title=Cults and Conservatives Spread Coronavirus in South Korea | access-date=4 March 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307042428/https://foreignpolicy.com/2020/02/27/coronavirus-south-korea-cults-conservatives-china/ | archive-date=7 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> Shincheonji denied this, and other sources report that the sect did cooperate with the authorities.<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/09/opinion/coronavirus-south-korea-church.html| title=Opinion &#124; Being Called a Cult is One Thing, Being Blamed for an Epidemic is Quite Another| newspaper=The New York Times| date=9 March 2020| last1=Rashid| first1=Raphael| access-date=21 March 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321153230/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/09/opinion/coronavirus-south-korea-church.html| archive-date=21 March 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> About half of confirmed cases were linked to the Shincheonji Church as of 27 February; this was verified by health officials.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://qz.com/1808390/religion-is-at-the-heart-of-koreas-coronavirus-outbreak/ | title=How religion is playing a role in the spread of coronavirus in Korea | access-date=12 March 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301081155/https://qz.com/1808390/religion-is-at-the-heart-of-koreas-coronavirus-outbreak/ | archive-date=1 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> As of 10 March, the KCDC was able to contact and test most of the Shincheonji Church members, with the total number of tests nationally standing at around 200,000.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===20 January \u2013 17 February===\n[[File:Shincheonji Daegu Church 9 20200302.jpg|thumb|left|Shincheonji Daegu Church]]\n[[File:0222 \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \uc608\ubc29\uc218\uce59 \ud3ec\uc2a4\ud130 \uc601\ubb38.jpg|thumb|right|Recommendations for preventing COVID-19 released by KCDC under the [[Ministry of Health and Welfare (South Korea)|Ministry of Health and Welfare]] of South Korea.]]\nOn 20 January, the first confirmed case was identified as a 35-year-old Chinese woman. The first South Korean national to be infected occurred three days later was a 55-year-old man who worked in Wuhan and returned for a checkup with flu symptoms. The two infection reports were publicly released on 24 January.<ref name=\"mk\"/>\n\nOn 26 January, a third case as a 54-year-old South Korean man. He had used a rental car and visited three restaurants, a hotel, a convenience store and met his family before admitting himself to hospital. All these places were disinfected.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 27 January, a fourth case was reported as a 55-year-old South Korean man who returned from Wuhan on 20 January. He first experienced flu symptoms on 21 January and suffered further complications four days later, eventually turning himself in. Both cases were tallied into formal records on 27 January.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=ko:\ud55c\uad6d \ub124\ubc88\uc9f8 '\uc2e0\uc885 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098' \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 \ubc1c\uc0dd\u202655\uc0b4 \ub0a8\uc131 |url=http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/925757.html |work=[[The Hankyoreh]] |accessdate=27 January 2020 |date=27 January 2020 |language=ko |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200127101855/http://www.hani.co.kr/arti/society/society_general/925757.html |archive-date=27 January 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February, an update on the first four patients indicated that the first three patients were showing weaker symptoms and recovering well while the fourth patient was getting treatment from [[pneumonia]]. Rumours circulated that the fourth patient had died which health authorities denied.<ref name=\"twelve\" />\n\nTwo more confirmed cases were reported on 30 January with the fifth patient being a 32-year-old South Korean man who returned from his work at Wuhan on 24 January. The sixth patient was the first case in South Korea who had never visited Wuhan. The 56-year-old man caught the virus when visiting a restaurant with the third patient.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=ko:\uc2e0\uc885\ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 2\uba85 \ub298\uc5b4\u00b7\u00b7\u00b76\ubc88\uc9f8 \ud658\uc790, \uad6d\ub0b4 \ucd5c\ucd08 '2\ucc28\uac10\uc5fc' |url=http://www.doctorstimes.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=209807 |website=\uc758\uc0ac\uc2e0\ubb38 |publisher=\uc774\ud55c\uc194 |accessdate=30 January 2020|date = 30 January 2020 |language=ko}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 January, a seventh patient was reported as a 28-year-old South Korean man returning from [[Wuhan]] on 23 January. He developed symptoms on 26 January, and was admitted to the hospital on 28 January.<ref>{{cite web |script-title=ko:'\uc2e0\uc885\ucf54\ub85c\ub098' 7\ubc88\uc9f8 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 \ubc1c\uc0dd\u2026\uc6b0\ud55c\uc11c \uc785\uad6d\ud55c 28\uc138 \ud55c\uad6d\ub0a8\uc131(\uc885\ud569) |url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LPOD&mid=sec&oid=001&aid=0011368450&isYeonhapFlash=Y&rc=N |website=Naver News |publisher=\uc5f0\ud569\ub274\uc2a4 |accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref> On the same day, four more patients were admitted into the record as the eighth patient, 62-year-old South Korean woman, returned from Wuhan. The ninth patient caught the virus from the fifth patient through direct contact while the tenth and the eleventh patient were the wife and child who were infected while visiting the sixth patient.<ref>{{cite news |script-title=ko:\uc2e0\uc885 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4: 11\ubc88\uc9f8 \ud658\uc790 \ud655\uc778...\ud604\uc7ac\uae4c\uc9c0 \ud655\uc9c4 \uc0ac\ub840 \uc815\ub9ac |url=https://www.bbc.com/korean/news-51320986 |newspaper=BBC News \ucf54\ub9ac\uc544 |accessdate=31 January 2020|date=31 January 2020 |language=ko}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 February, a 49-year-old Chinese national working in [[Japan]] as a tour guide was confirmed as the twelfth patient. He caught the virus while visiting a Japanese patient in Japan and entered South Korea through [[Gimpo International Airport]] on 19 January.<ref name=\"twelve\">{{cite web |script-title=ko:'\uc2e0\uc885\ucf54\ub85c\ub098'\uad6d\ub0b4 12\ubc88\uc9f8 \ud658\uc790\u2026\uc77c\ubcf8\ud658\uc790 \uc811\ucd09 49\uc138 \uc911\uad6d\ub0a8\uc131(\uc885\ud569) |url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LPOD&mid=sec&oid=001&aid=0011370927&isYeonhapFlash=Y&rc=N |website=Naver |publisher=Yonhap News Agency |accessdate=1 February 2020 |language=ko}}</ref> The KCDC confirmed an additional three cases on 2 February, bringing the total to fifteen.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200202000651320|title=S. Korea Reports 3 More Cases of Novel Coronavirus, Total Now at 15|first=|date=2 February 2020|website=Yonhap News Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202014910/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200202000651320|archive-date=2 February 2020|access-date=2 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nA woman, who had returned from [[Thailand]] after a five-day vacation, was tested positive and confirmed as the sixteenth case on 4 February.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: South Korean woman travelling home from Thailand tests positive for virus |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korean-woman-travelling-home-from-thailand-tests-positive-for-virus |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=4 February 2020 |date=4 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204092646/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/coronavirus-south-korean-woman-travelling-home-from-thailand-tests-positive-for-virus |archive-date=4 February 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Three more cases were confirmed on 5 February, bringing the total case count to 19. The seventeenth and nineteenth patients had attended a conference in Singapore and been in contact with an infected individual there.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yna.kr/AEN20200205002356320|title=3 More Virus Cases Bring S. Korea's Total to 19, Two Confirmed after Trip to Singapore|last=|first=|date=5 February 2020|website=Yonhap|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=5 February 2020}}</ref> The very same day the KCDC announced that the second patient had been released from hospital after being tested negative in consecutive tests, becoming the country's first coronavirus patient to fully recover.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200205006252320|title=S. Korea Releases First Fully Recovered Coronavirus Patient from Hospital|last=|first=|date=5 February 2020|website=Yonhap News Agency|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205133506/https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200205006252320|archive-date=5 February 2020|access-date=5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible mw-collapsed\"\n|+ {{nowrap|Details of the first 30 confirmed cases in South Korea (As of 17 February 2020)}}\n! Case\n! Date\n! Age\n! Gender\n! Nationality\n! Place of stay\n! Hospital of admission\n! Visited Wuhan?\n! Entry date\n! Status\n! Contacts of case\n! Note\n! Source\n|-\n|1\n|20 January 2020\n|35\n|Female\n|Chinese\n|[[Incheon]]\n|Incheon Metropo