 National University]] Hospital, [[Gwangju]]\n|No\n|19 January 2020 (Thailand)\n|Discharged (19 February 2020)\n|450\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|17\n|5 February 2020\n|37\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Guri\n|Myongji Hospital, [[Goyang]]\n|No\n|24 January 2020 (Singapore)\n|Discharged (12 February 2020)\n|290\n|Related to cases at Grand Hyatt Singapore\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|18\n|5 February 2020\n|20\n|Female\n|Korean\n|Gwangju\n|[[Chonnam National University]] Hospital, [[Gwangju]]\n|No\n|19 January 2020 (Thailand)\n|Discharged (19 February 2020)\n|8\n|Daughter of case 16\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|19\n|5 February 2020\n|36\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Seoul\n|Seoul Metropolitan City Seoul Medical Center, [[Seoul]]\n|No\n|23 January 2020 (Singapore)\n|Discharged (21 February 2020)\n|68\n|Related to cases at Grand Hyatt Singapore\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|20\n|5 February 2020\n|41\n|Female\n|Korean\n|Suwon\n|Korean Armed Forces Capital Hospital, [[Seongnam]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (24 February 2020)\n|2\n|Sister-in-law of case 15\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|21\n|5 February 2020\n|59\n|Female\n|Korean\n|Seoul\n|[[Seoul National University Hospital]], [[Seoul]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (29 February 2020)\n|6\n|Friend of case 6\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|22\n|6 February 2020\n|46\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Naju\n|[[Chosun University]] Hospital, [[Gwangju]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (15 February 2020)\n|1\n|Brother of case 16\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|23\n|6 February 2020\n|57\n|Female\n|Chinese\n|Seoul\n|National Medical Center, [[Seoul]]\n|Yes\n|23 January 2020\n|Discharged (29 February 2020)\n|23\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|24\n|6 February 2020\n|28\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Asan\n|National Medical Center, [[Seoul]]\n|Yes\n|31 January 2020\n|Discharged (27 February 2020)\n|0\n|Passenger on board the evacuation flights from Wuhan\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|25\n|9 February 2020\n|73\n|Female\n|Korean\n|Siheung\n|[[Seoul National University Bundang Hospital]], [[Seongnam]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (5 March 2020)\n|12\n|Mother of case 26\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|26\n|9 February 2020\n|51\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Siheung\n|Gyeonggi Provincial Medical Center Anseong Hospital, [[Anseong]]\n|No\n|31 January 2020 (Guangdong)\n|Discharged (8 March 2020)\n|12\n|\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|27\n|9 February 2020\n|37\n|Female\n|Chinese\n|Siheung\n|Gyeonggi Provincial Medical Center Anseong Hospital, [[Anseong]]\n|No\n|31 January 2020 (Guangdong)\n|Discharged (7 March 2020)\n|38\n|Wife of case 26\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|28\n|10 February 2020\n|30\n|Female\n|Chinese\n|Goyang\n|Myongji Hospital, [[Goyang]]\n|Yes\n|20 January 2020\n|Discharged (17 February 2020)\n|1\n|Friend of case 3\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|29\n|16 February 2020\n|82\n|Male\n|Korean\n|Seoul\n|[[Seoul National University Hospital]], [[Seoul]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (March 2020)\n|117\n|Friend of case 83\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|-\n|30\n|16 February 2020\n|68\n|Female\n|Korean\n|Seoul\n|[[Seoul National University Hospital]], [[Seoul]]\n|No\n|(Infection in Domestic)\n|Discharged (March 2020)\n|27\n|Wife of case 29\n|<ref name=\"YNA\"/><ref name=\"KCDCDaily\"/>\n|}\n\n===18 February \u2013 29 February===\n{{anchor|Daegu outbreak}}\n[[File:2020 coronavirus cases in South Korea.svg|350px|thumb|left|[[Epidemic curve]] of COVID-19 in South Korea]]\n\nOn 18 February, South Korea confirmed its 31st case in Daegu, a member of the [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony|Shincheonji]] religious organisation. The patient continued to go to gatherings of Shincheonji days after showing symptoms, which are typically held with people in very close proximity and include physical contact of the members. Many of the patient's close contacts would turn out to be infected, triggering a drastic escalation of the South Korean spread of confirmed cases of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]] infection.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Farrer|first=Martin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-south-korea-sees-huge-jump-cases-china-hubei-wuhan-outbreak-|title=Coronavirus: South Korea cluster drives huge rise in cases|date=22 February 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=4 March 2020|last2=agencies|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305220400/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/22/coronavirus-south-korea-sees-huge-jump-cases-china-hubei-wuhan-outbreak-|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=fp20200227/>\n\nOn 19 February, the number of confirmed cases increased by 20. On 20 February 70<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" /> new cases were confirmed, giving a total of 104 confirmed cases, according to the KCDC. According to ''[[Reuters]]'', KCDC attributed the sudden jump of 70 cases linked to \"Patient No. 31\", who had participated in a gathering in [[Daegu]] at the Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony.<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" />\n\nOn 20 February, the streets of Daegu were empty in reaction to the Shincheonji outbreak. A resident described the reaction, stating \"It's like someone dropped a bomb in the middle of the city. It looks like a zombie apocalypse.\"<ref name=\"ThomReut_SKorea_zombie\" /> The first death was reported<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/south-korea-reports-first-coronavirus-death-infections-linked-church-rise-n1139821|title=South Korea reports first coronavirus death as infections linked to church rise|website=NBC News|language=en|access-date=21 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310234601/https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/south-korea-reports-first-coronavirus-death-infections-linked-church-rise-n1139821|archive-date=10 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> in a mental ward of Cheongdo Daenam Hospital in [[Cheongdo County]]. According to the mayor of Daegu, the number of suspected cases as of 21 February was 544 among 4,400 examined followers of the church.<ref>{{cite web |title=\uc2e0\ucc9c\uc9c0 \uad00\ub828 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 76\uba85\uc73c\ub85c \ub298\uc5b4...\ub300\uad6c \uad50\uc778 \uc758\uc2ec\uc790\ub9cc 544\uba85 |publisher=Chosun.com |date=21 February 2020 |url=https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/02/21/2020022101558.html |access-date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102756/https://news.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2020/02/21/2020022101558.html |archive-date=26 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> The hospital was suspected as the source of the present outbreak after it was visited by a woman who became the second fatal case of South Korea on that day. Upon investigation, it was determined that the infection had spread to that hospital through a funeral ceremony attended by members of the church.<ref name=\"b82186\" /><ref name=\"koreabiomed\">{{cite news |last1=Lee |first1=Han-soo |title=COVID-19 patients soar to 204 in Korea |url=http://www.koreabiomed.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=7489 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=Korea Biomedical Review |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102842/http://www.koreabiomed.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=7489 |archive-date=26 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAll South Korean military bases were on lockdown after tests confirmed three soldiers to be positive for the virus.<ref name=\"b82186\">{{Cite news|url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51582186|title = South Korea virus 'emergency' as cases increase|work = BBC News|date = 21 February 2020|access-date = 21 February 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200307193706/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51582186|archive-date = 7 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref> Airlines cut connections and cultural schedules were being canceled due to fears of further spread.<ref>{{cite news |title=Airlines to suspend more flights over coronavirus |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000249 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=Korea Herald |agency=Yonhap |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221023912/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000249 |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Song |first1=Seung-hyun |title=Foreign artists delay concerts in Korea due to spread of COVID-19 |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000554 |accessdate=21 February 2020 |work=Korea Herald |date=21 February 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200221190026/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200221000554 |archive-date=21 February 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[United States Forces Korea]] raised the alert level from low to moderate and cut off non-essential travel to and from USFK Daegu.<ref name=\"MT\">{{cite web|url = https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/02/19/us-forces-korea-imposes-new-coronavirus-protections-after-uptick-in-s-korea-cases/|title = US Forces Korea imposes new coronavirus protections after uptick in S Korea cases|date = 19 February 2020|access-date = 23 February 2020|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20200306190234/https://www.militarytimes.com/news/your-military/2020/02/19/us-forces-korea-imposes-new-coronavirus-protections-after-uptick-in-s-korea-cases/|archive-date = 6 March 2020|url-status = live}}</ref> USFK Daegu's school facilities were closed and non-essential personnel were ordered to stay at home while any visitors going there were not allowed to enter.<ref name=\"MT\" /> USFK announced that the widow of a retired soldier who was in Daegu was diagnosed to be positive for the virus on 24 February.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/usfk-dependent-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-putting-military-on-high-alert-in-south-korea-1.620023 | title=USFK dependent tests positive for coronavirus, putting military on high alert in South Korea | access-date=25 February 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102852/https://www.stripes.com/news/pacific/usfk-dependent-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-putting-military-on-high-alert-in-south-korea-1.620023 | archive-date=26 February 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> [[Camp Humphreys]] enacted virus detection protocols, including temperature checks and raised the alert level to high.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.businessinsider.com/us-forces-korea-high-alert-for-coronavirus-after-positive-test-2020-2 | title=US troops in Korea are on high alert for coronavirus after widow of retired soldier tests positive | access-date=25 February 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200227153541/https://www.businessinsider.com/us-forces-korea-high-alert-for-coronavirus-after-positive-test-2020-2 | archive-date=27 February 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref> On 26 February, an American soldier based at Camp Carroll was diagnosed to be positive and was quarantined away from bases via off-base housing unit<ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-southkorea/us-soldier-infected-as-south-korea-coronavirus-cases-rise-above-1260-idUSKCN20K045| title=U.S. Soldier infected as South Korea coronavirus cases rise above 1,260| newspaper=Reuters| date=26 February 2020| access-date=26 February 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303231232/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-southkorea/us-soldier-infected-as-south-korea-coronavirus-cases-rise-above-1260-idUSKCN20K045| archive-date=3 March 2020| url-status=live}}</ref> with contact tracing done that showed his movements to Camp Walker.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.marketwatch.com/story/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-continue-to-soar-towns-sealed-off-in-northern-italy-2020-02-25 | title=First U.S. Soldier in South Korea tests positive for coronavirus; towns sealed off in northern Italy | access-date=26 February 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305134342/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-continue-to-soar-towns-sealed-off-in-northern-italy-2020-02-25 | archive-date=5 March 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAs of 22 February, among 9,336 followers of the church, 1,261 reported symptoms.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mohw.go.kr/react/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=353047&SEARCHKEY=TITLE&SEARCHVALUE=%EC%BD%94%EB%A1%9C%EB%82%98%EB%B0%94%EC%9D%B4%EB%9F%AC|script-title=ko:\ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uac10\uc5fc\uc99d-19 \uad6d\ub0b4 \ubc1c\uc0dd \ud604\ud669 (2\uc6d4 22\uc77c 09\uc2dc)|first=|date=22 February 2020|url-status=live|title=Archived copy|access-date=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200226102804/http://www.mohw.go.kr/react/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=353047&SEARCHKEY=TITLE&SEARCHVALUE=%EC%BD%94%EB%A1%9C%EB%82%98%EB%B0%94%EC%9D%B4%EB%9F%AC|archive-date=26 February 2020}}</ref> At the time, 169 confirmed cases involved the same church and another 111 came from the Cheongdo Daenam Hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdc.go.kr/|script-title=ko:\uc9c8\ubcd1\uad00\ub9ac\ubcf8\ubd80|website=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention Korea|title=Archived copy|access-date=22 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130022550/http://www.cdc.go.kr/|archive-date=30 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> 23 February saw another 123 cases with 75 being from Shincheonji<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366303&tag=&nPage=1 |title= 123 additional cases have been confirmed |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 23 February 2020 |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher=  |access-date= 24 February 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200223090022/https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366303&tag=&nPage=1 |archive-date= 23 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> and 24 February saw 161 additional cases with 129 being from the same religious group. Over 27,000 people have been tested for the virus with 19,127 negative results.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366323&tag=&nPage=1 |title= 161 additional cases have been confirmed |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 24 February 2020 |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher=  |access-date= 24 February 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200224201926/https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366323&tag=&nPage=1 |archive-date= 24 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nOn 24 February, 15 countries imposed travel restrictions to and from South Korea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-24-20-hnk-intl/h_303decf2bc32dd08ce587a7e9f3efafd|title=15 countries have travel restrictions on South Korea|last=|first=|date=24 February 2020|website=CNN|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200224070457/https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-24-20-hnk-intl/h_303decf2bc32dd08ce587a7e9f3efafd|archive-date=24 February 2020|access-date=24 February 2020}}</ref> It was also reported that a senior health official overseeing the COVID-19 efforts in Daegu tested positive and was also a member of Shincheonji.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3052129/coronavirus-infected-health-official-leading-south |title= Coronavirus: infected health official leading South Korea's fight against Covid-19 is member of Shincheonji Church of Jesus doomsday cult |last= Park |first= Chan-kyong |date= 24 February 2020 |website= [[South China Morning Post]] |publisher=  |access-date= 25 February 2020 |quote= Official in charge of fight against the virus in western Daegu admits being member of cult after testing positive; 50 coworkers quarantined |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200225032613/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3052129/coronavirus-infected-health-official-leading-south |archive-date= 25 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref name=\":750tested\"/> Within a few days, a petition to the nation's president urging for the disbandment of the church had over 750,000 signatures. Their headquarters in [[Gwacheon]] was raided by law enforcement and government officials said all 245,000 members of the religious group would be found and tested.<ref name=\":750tested\">{{cite web |url= https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-27/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-surveillance |title= Were you on this bus with a coronavirus patient? South Korea is on the hunt for infections |last= Kim |first= Victoria |date= 27 February 2020 |website= [[Los Angeles Times]] |publisher=  |access-date= 28 February 2020 |quote= Even a public health official in charge of infection prevention in Seo-gu in Daegu was revealed to be a member of the church after he was diagnosed with the virus. Many members hide their affiliation with the controversial church. More than 750,000 signed a petition to the South Korean president urging that the church be disbanded. Authorities in Gyeonggi province raided the group\u2019s headquarters in the city of Gwacheon, alleging that the church had been slow to turn over its list of members. South Korean officials said they would track down and test all 245,000 members of the church. |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200227235952/https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-02-27/south-korea-coronavirus-cases-surveillance |archive-date= 27 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February, over 2,000 confirmed cases were reported.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366398&tag=&nPage=1 |title= The Updates of COVID-19 in Republic of Korea As of 28 February 2020 |author= <!--Not stated--> |date=  |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher=  |access-date= 28 February 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200229165550/https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366398&tag=&nPage=1 |archive-date= 29 February 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===March===\nOn 2 March, there were over 4,200 confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366416&tag=&nPage=1 |title= 476 additional cases are confirmed |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher= |access-date= 2 March 2020 |quote= As of 0:00, 2 March 2020, 476 additional cases are confirmed, compared to yesterday afternoon (16:00, 1 March) which brings in total number of confirmed cases to 4,212.}}</ref> With an additional 4,000 cases of COVID-19 within two weeks, and roughly 60% of the total infections nationwide having stemmed from the church, the Seoul city government asked prosecutors to press charges against the religious group's founder and senior members for murder, causing harm, and for violating the Infectious Disease and Control Act.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://finance.yahoo.com/news/seoul-city-seeks-murder-charges-against-sect-founder-025259454.html |title= Seoul city seeks murder charges against sect founder over virus |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 2 March 2020 |website= [[Yahoo!]] |publisher= [[Agence France-Presse]] |access-date= 4 March 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200302103858/https://finance.yahoo.com/news/seoul-city-seeks-murder-charges-against-sect-founder-025259454.html |archive-date= 2 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> Interviews have occurred with all 230,000 members of the religious group and nearly 9,000 were said to be showing symptoms of the virus.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51695649 |title= Coronavirus: South Korea sect leader to face probe over deaths |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 2 March 2020 |website= [[BBC]] |publisher=  |access-date= 4 March 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303014749/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51695649 |archive-date= 3 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> Due to the number of infections in the country, ninety-five countries have banned or limited entry for South Korean passport holders.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/how-south-korea-lost-control-of-its-coronavirus-outbreak |title= How South Korea Lost Control of Its Coronavirus Outbreak |last= Kim |first= Suki |date= 4 March 2020 |website= [[The New Yorker]] |publisher=  |access-date= 5 March 2020 |quote= Citing the number of covid-19 diagnoses in South Korea, ninety-five countries, including China and Japan, now ban or limit entry by South Korean nationals. |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200305132902/https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/how-south-korea-lost-control-of-its-coronavirus-outbreak |archive-date= 5 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> Testing is also conducted at drive-through testing sites where patients do not leave their vehicles, but are met by medical personnel in hazmat suits over several stations. The process is completed in a few minutes and results come in several days.<ref name=cnn20200302>{{cite web |url= https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/02/asia/coronavirus-drive-through-south-korea-hnk-intl/index.html |title= South Korea pioneers coronavirus drive-through testing station |last1= Watson |first1= Ivan |last2= Jeong |first2= Sophie |date= 3 March 2020 |website= [[CNN]] |publisher=  |access-date= 5 March 2020 |quote=  |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200305011008/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/03/02/asia/coronavirus-drive-through-south-korea-hnk-intl/index.html |archive-date= 5 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref>\nOn 8 March, [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|KCDC]] in South Korea announced that 79.4% of confirmed COVID-19 cases were related to group infection. KCDC also announced that outbreak associated with [[Shincheonji Church of Jesus the Temple of the Tabernacle of the Testimony|Shincheonji Church]] totaled 4,482 infections, accounting for 62.8% of the total confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite news|script-title=ko:[\ucd9c\ucc98: \uc911\uc559\uc77c\ubcf4] [\ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uc885\ud569] \uc11c\uc6b8\ubc31\ubcd1\uc6d0 \ud658\uc790 1\uba85 \ud655\uc9c4\u2026\"\ub300\uad6c \uac70\uc8fc \uc228\uae30\uace0 \ub0b4\uc6d0\" |url=https://news.joins.com/article/23724705 |work=[[JoongAng Ilbo]] |language=ko-kr}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.koreatimes.co.kr/pages/article.asp?newsIdx=285870|title=New cases of infections drop for third day|date=9 March 2020|website=m.koreatimes.co.kr|accessdate=11 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310190619/https://m.koreatimes.co.kr/pages/article.asp?newsIdx=285870|archive-date=10 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n13 March was the first time since the outbreak on 20 January in which the number of recoveries, 177, was larger than the number of those who newly tested positive, 110.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.mk.co.kr/news/it/view/2020/03/265693 |title= \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 '\uace8\ub4e0\ud06c\ub85c\uc2a4'\u2026\uc644\uce58>\uc2e0\uaddc \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 |author1= \uc11c\uc9c4\uc6b0 |author2= \uc774\uc11d\ud76c |author3= \uc6b0\uc131\ub355 |date= 13 March 2020 |website= \ub9e4\uc77c\uacbd\uc81c MBN |publisher=  |access-date= 17 March 2020 |quote=  |language= Korean |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319095345/https://www.mk.co.kr/news/it/view/2020/03/265693/ |archive-date= 19 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200315/100164765/1 |title= \ub300\uad6c\uc11c \ucf54\ub85c\ub09819 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 \ubcf4\ub2e4 \uc644\uce58\uc790 \ub9ce\uc740 '\uace8\ub4e0\ud06c\ub85c\uc2a4' \ud655\uc5f0 |author= <!--Not stated--> |date= 15 March 2020 |website= DongA |publisher=  |access-date= 17 March 2020 |quote=  |language= Korean |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200315182415/http://www.donga.com/news/article/all/20200315/100164765/1 |archive-date= 15 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.newdaily.co.kr/site/data/html/2020/03/15/2020031500028.html |title= 15\uc77c \uc6b0\ud55c\ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \ud655\uc9c4\uc790 8162\uba85\u2026'\uace8\ub4e0 \ud06c\ub85c\uc2a4' \uc0ac\ud758\uc9f8 |author= \uae40\ub3d9\uc6b0 |date= 15 March 2020 |website= New Daily |publisher=  |access-date= 17 March 2020 |quote=  |language= Korean |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319095344/http://www.newdaily.co.kr/site/data/html/2020/03/15/2020031500028.html |archive-date= 19 March 2020 |url-status= live }}</ref> <!--- This part is an analysis from South Korean media, please do not delete this section without any farther discussion on the talk page---> However, with the recent cluster of cases in the [[Seoul Capital Area]], there are new fears that infections may rise sharply.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/commentary/covid-19-coronavirus-south-korea-success-testing-tracking-model-12567158 |title=Commentary: South Korea has been exemplary. Even then, it hasn't slayed COVID-19 |access-date=24 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200324084938/https://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/commentary/covid-19-coronavirus-south-korea-success-testing-tracking-model-12567158 |archive-date=24 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe controversy about Shincheonji also continued, and generated international interest. After the lawsuit started by the Mayor of Seoul, the police raided the church premises to check whether the list of members supplied by Shincheonji pursuant to a request by the authorities was, as the Mayor argued, not complete. The authorities checked the list seized during the raid with the one Shincheonji had supplied, and concluded that discrepancies were minor.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kim |first=So-hyun |date=17 March 2020 |title='Shincheonji didn't lie about membership figures' |url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200317000667 |work=The Korea Herald |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318185856/http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20200317000667 |archive-date=18 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Commission on International Religious Freedom]] (USCIRF) expressed concern that religious freedom rights of Shincheonji members may be violated in South Korea by \"exaggerating the church's role in the outbreak,\" and stated that, \"USCIRF has received reports of individuals encountering discrimination at work and spousal abuse because of their affiliation with the church.\"<ref name=\"USCIRF\">{{cite web |url=https://www.uscirf.gov/sites/default/files/2020%20Factsheet%20Covid-19%20and%20FoRB.pdf |title=The Global Response to the Coronavirus: Impact on Religious Practice and Religious Freedom |last=U.S. Commission on International Religious Freedom |date=March 2020|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref> USCIRF reported that South Korean \"Vice Minister of Health Kim Kang-lip has publicly stated that the Shincheonji church has cooperated with authorities.\"<ref name=\"USCIRF\"/> The Belgian NGO [[Human Rights Without Frontiers]] and [[CESNUR]] released a \"White Paper\" claiming that, although it did make \"mistakes\" in its management of the crisis, Shincheonji had also been discriminated because of its status as an unpopular group in South Korea.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Human Rights without frontiers release white paper on Coronavirus |url=https://m.risingbd.com/english/national/news/68988/Human-Rights-without-frontiers-release-white-paper-on-Coronavirus |work=[[Risingbd.com]] |location=[[Dhaka]] |date=18 March 2020 |access-date=19 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319233319/https://m.risingbd.com/english/national/news/68988/Human-Rights-without-frontiers-release-white-paper-on-Coronavirus |archive-date=19 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Mener kristen sekt er utsatt for jakt p\u00e5 syndebukk for koronautbruddet |url=https://www.vl.no/nyhet/mener-kristen-sekt-er-utsatt-for-jakt-pa-syndebukk-for-koronautbruddet-1.1691863?paywall=true |work=[[V\u00e5rt Land (Norwegian newspaper)|V\u00e5rt Land]] |location=Oslo |date=March 31, 2020 |access-date=April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, around 79 church devotees were infected with the virus after attending the [[River of Grace Community Church]]. The infections were claimed to have been caused by spraying salt-water into followers' mouths, under the belief that this would protect them from the virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|title=Coronavirus: saltwater spray infects 46 church-goers in South Korea|date=16 March 2020|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074249/https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3075421/coronavirus-salt-water-spray-infects-46-church-goers|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|title=South Korea church used saltwater spray amid coronavirus outbreak|website=UPI|language=en|access-date=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318074251/https://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2020/03/16/South-Korea-church-used-saltwater-spray-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/9881584365228/|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Nearly 140 churches in Gyeonggi Province, which surrounds Seoul and is part of the [[Greater Seoul Area]], will be closed if they do not implement preventative measures, including temperature checks, two-meter separation, and the wearing of masks.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.scmp.com/news/asia/east-asia/article/3075527/coronavirus-south-korea-threatens-close-churches-not-enforcing |title= Coronavirus: South Korea threatens to close churches for not enforcing preventive measures |author= <!--Not stated--> |date=17 March 2020 |website= [[South China Morning Post]] |publisher= Reuters and Associated Press |access-date= 31 March 2020 |quote= }}</ref> As more churches are holding services despite a government order for social distancing, on 30 March, the controversial Manmin Central Church in Guro, Seoul became a cluster with 22 infections linked to a gathering in early March in which the group was preparing stock footage to use for online worship services. Other church clusters have appears in the cities of Suwon, Busan, Geochang, and Bucheon.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.scmp.com/week-asia/health-environment/article/3077497/coronavirus-cluster-emerges-another-south-korean |title= Coronavirus cluster emerges at another South Korean church, as others press ahead with Sunday services\n|author= Park Chan-kyong |date= 30 March 2020 |website= [[South China Morning Post]] |publisher= |access-date= 31 March 2020 |quote= }}</ref>\n\n===April \u2013 present outbreak===\nAs infection rates have risen outside Korea leading to increases of sick arriving in the country (476 of 9,661 cases were imported as of 30 March), the KCDC will be implanting stronger infectious disease control measures for travelers coming from overseas as of 1 April. Additionally, new self-quarantine measures for travelers coming from Europe or the United States will be in effect from the same day. For example, those showing symptoms but test negative, and those who are without symptoms and are staying short-term in Korea, need to quarantine for two weeks in a government provided facility.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cdc.go.kr/board/board.es?mid=a30402000000&bid=0030&act=view&list_no=366687&tag=&nPage=2 |title= The updates on COVID-19 in Korea as of 30 March |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 30 March 2020 |website= [[Korea Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] |publisher= |access-date= 31 March 2020 |quote= }}</ref> Costs for the stay at the facility are the responsibility of the individual and total 100,000 won (US$81) per day.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2020/04/119_287412.html |title= Korea deports Taiwanese woman for refusing to stay at quarantine facility |author= Jung Min-ho |date= 6 April 2020 |website= The Korea Times |publisher= |access-date= 7 April 2020 |quote=  }}</ref> Afew days later, a Taiwanese woman was deported on 5 April for refusing to stay in a quarantine facility as she initially agreed and then later disagreed with paying for the cost of staying at the government designated facility, reportedly costing around 100,000 won per day.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200406004451315|title=(LEAD) Taiwanese woman deported for refusing to stay at quarantine facility|last=\uc774\ubbfc\uc9c0|date=2020-04-06|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n45 people are being investigated by the police for allegedly violating COVID-19 self-isolation. Under the revised anti-infectious disease law, violators can face up to a year in prison, a 10 million won fine, or in the case of foreign passport holders\u2014deportation.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/nation/2020/04/177_287168.html |title= Coronavirus: 45 under police investigation for breaking self-isolation rules |author= Park Si-soo |date= 1 April 2020 |website= The Korea Times |publisher= |access-date= 2 April 2020 |quote= }}</ref> \n\nSeeing the [[Misinformation related to the 2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic|infodemic]] on COVID-19 information starting in China and spreading to Korea and the US, fake news researcher [[Cha Meeyoung]] of [[KAIST]] and the [[Institute for Basic Science]], along with researchers from [[Ewha Womans University]], started the multilingual Facts Before Rumors campaign to separate common claims seen online.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000739/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18241 |title= \u201cFact before rumors\u201d campaign just began by the IBS Data Science Group |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 26 March 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |publisher= |access-date= 31 March 2020 |quote= }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.ibs.re.kr/cop/bbs/BBSMSTR_000000000971/selectBoardArticle.do?nttId=18234&pageIndex=1&searchCnd=&searchWrd= |title= \ucf54\ub85c\ub098\ubc14\uc774\ub7ec\uc2a4\uc640 \uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9 |author=[[Cha Meeyoung]] |date= 24 March 2020 |website= [[Institute for Basic Science]] |publisher= |access-date= 30 March 2020 |quote= |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://dongascience.donga.com/news.php?idx=35457 |title= \"\ub3d9\ub0a8\uc544\u00b7\ub0a8\ubbf8 \ucf54\ub85c\ub098 \uac00\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4 \ub9c9\uace0 '\uc9c4\uc9dc\ub274\uc2a4' \uc804\ud558\uc790\" \uad6d\ub0b4 \uacfc\ud559\uc790 \ud314 \uac77\uc5b4 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 25 March 2020 |website= Donga Science |publisher= |access-date= 30 March 2020 |quote= |language= Korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hankyung.com/opinion/article/2020032509531 |title= [\ucc28\ubbf8\uc601\uc758 \ub370\uc774\ud130\ub85c \ubcf8 \uc138\uc0c1] '\uc778\ud3ec\ub370\ubbf9'\uc758 \uc2dc\ub300 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 25 March 2020 |website= \ud55c\uad6d\uacbd\uc81c |publisher= |access-date= 30 March 2020 |quote= |language= Korean}}</ref>\n\nA Canadian cast member with the touring ''[[The Phantom of the Opera (1986 musical)|The Phantom of the Opera]]'' stage play entered Korea on March 12, participated for roughly two weeks, and tested positive 2 April. An American colleague tested positive on 4 April, which shut down production of the musical until 14 April while the venue could be disinfected and contacts of the staff, those staying in the same hotel, and over 8,000 people who recently attended were contacted by health authorities who told them to stay indoors and contact a testing center if they develop symptoms.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/art/2020/04/398_287384.html |title= Over 8,000 audience members to be monitored after musical actors test positive for COVID-19 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date= 5 April 2020 |website= The Korea Times |publisher= Yonhap News |access-date= 7 April 2020 |quote= More than 8,000 people who attended the musical \"Phantom of the Opera\" in Seoul will be closely monitored after two cast members tested positive for the novel coronavirus, authorities said Friday.}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/South Korea medical cases chart}}\n[[File:CoViD-19 KR.svg|thumb|right|upright=2|Number of cases (blue) and number of deaths (red) on a [[logarithmic scale]].]]\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n | width = 500\n | type = line\n | xAxisTitle=Date\n | yAxisTitle=Cases\n | xAxisAngle = -70\n | legend=Legend\n | x = 1/19, 1/20, 1/21, 1/22, 1/23, 1/24, 1/25, 1/26, 1/27, 1/28, 1/29, 1/30, 1/31, 2/1, 2/2, 2/3, 2/4, 2/5, 2/6, 2/7, 2/8, 2/9, 2/10, 2/11, 2/12, 2/13, 2/14, 2/15, 2/16, 2/17, 2/18, 2/19, 2/20, 2/21, 2/22, 2/23, 2/24, 2/25, 2/26, 2/27, 2/28, 2/29, 3/