{"title_page": "Vietnam at the Southeast Asian Games", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n \n{{Infobox country at games|NOC=VIE|NOCname=[[Vietnam Olympic Committee]]|oldcode=|games=Southeast Asian Games|gold=928|silver=967|bronze=991|rank=6|appearances=*[[1989 Southeast Asian Games|1989]]\n*[[1991 Southeast Asian Games|1991]]\n*[[1993 Southeast Asian Games|1993]]\n*[[1995 Southeast Asian Games|1995]]\n*[[1997 Southeast Asian Games|1997]]\n*[[1999 Southeast Asian Games|1999]]\n*[[2001 Southeast Asian Games|2001]]\n*[[2003 Southeast Asian Games|2003]]\n*[[2005 Southeast Asian Games|2005]]\n*[[2007 Southeast Asian Games|2007]]\n*[[2009 Southeast Asian Games|2009]]\n*[[2011 Southeast Asian Games|2011]]\n*[[2013 Southeast Asian Games|2013]]\n*[[2015 Southeast Asian Games|2015]]\n*[[2017 Southeast Asian Games|2017]]\n*[[2019 Southeast Asian Games|2019]]|seealso=|website=}}'''[[Vietnam]]''' first sent their athletes to compete in the [[Southeast Asian Games]] in the [[1989 Southeast Asian Games]] in [[Kuala Lumpur]], [[Malaysia]]. Vietnam has hosted the games only once in [[2003 Southeast Asian Games|2003]] but is now hosting the [[2021 Southeast Asian Games]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.ph/life/guide/a-brief-12-year-history-of-how-sea-games-countries-wielded-their-host-s-advantage-a1017-20191216-lfrm|title=A brief 12-year history of how SEA Games countries wielded their 'host\u2019s advantage'|date=2019-12-16|website=Spin.ph|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocasia.org/NOC/CountryDetails?q=CHior5e3Ns5hlIyB8twKf2qL9i90lW+mCLHVow0NgP4=|title=Vietnam NOC - Olympic Council of Asia|website=www.ocasia.org|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\nVietnam has won 928 Gold Medals, 967 Silver Medals, and 991 Bronze Medals totaling to 2,886 medals all in all since 1989.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocasia.org/Game/GHAFDetails?q=XHreq1g4oYTZIf3o6y9FFscVG8BWx29pF4p9I39blYhgmp9N8LGL4zzJq2wWAfesdIRJJZycWY9NdPLhmTsG8g==|title=Kuala Lumpur 1965 - Olympic Council of Asia|website=www.ocasia.org|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> Unfortunately, Vietnam has not topped the Medal Tally in any Southeast Asian Game instead in 2003 when they hosted it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.ph/life/guide/a-brief-12-year-history-of-how-sea-games-countries-wielded-their-host-s-advantage-a1017-20191216-lfrm|title=A brief 12-year history of how SEA Games countries wielded their 'host\u2019s advantage'|date=2019-12-16|website=Spin.ph|language=en|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ocasia.org/NOC/CountryDetails?q=CHior5e3Ns5hlIyB8twKf2qL9i90lW+mCLHVow0NgP4=|title=Vietnam NOC - Olympic Council of Asia|website=www.ocasia.org|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n== Medal Tally ==\n\n* In 1959 until 1973, Vietnam has won medals under South Vietnam. These are only the medals they won as a unified Vietnam\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable \u201dwikitable sortable\u201d\" style=\"\u201dtext-align;center;\"\n|+'''All-time Medal Tally'''\n!Games\n!Athletes\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#F7F6A8;\" width=\"40\" |{{Gold01}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#DCE5E5;\" width=\"40\" |{{Silver02}}\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"background:#FFDAB9;\" width=\"40\" |{{Bronze03}}\n! width=\"40\" |Total\n! width=\"40\" |Rank\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |{{flagicon|MAS}} [[1989 Southeast Asian Games|1989 Kuala Lumpur]]\n|?\n| style=\"background:#F7F6A8;\" |3\n| style=\"background:#DCE5E5;\" |11\n| style=\"background:#FFDAB9;\" |5\n|'''''19'''''\n|7\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |{{flagicon|PHI}} [[1991 Southeast Asian Games|1991 Manila]]\n|?\n| style=\"background:#F7F6A8;\" |7\n| style=\"background:#DCE5E5;\" |12\n| style=\"background:#FFDAB9;\" |10\n|'''''29'''''\n|7\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |{{flagicon|SGP}} [[1993 Southeast Asian Games|1993 Singapore]]\n|?\n| style=\"background:#F7F6A8;\" |9\n| style=\"background:#DCE5E5;\" |6\n| style=\"background:#FFDAB9;\" |19\n|'''''34'''''\n|6\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |{{flagicon|THA}